         strengthens authoritative personnel data, improves interoperability across Navy and Department of War systems, enhances
         cybersecurity, and incrementally consolidates legacy manpower and personnel capabilities into a modern personnel
         transaction environment. (Baseline: $0)
      ii)MyNavy HR IT Modernization and Sustainment: Net-zero program adjustment from Legacy System Sustainment into                            20,718
         MyNavy HR IT Modernization and Sustainment to execute the CNP's directive to update MyNavy HR enterprise systems.
         (Baseline: $109,214)
      iii)Personnel and Manpower Support Programs: Increased funding is required to field and sustain essential data collection and             13,300
         analysis tools. These instruments are necessary to measure the effectiveness of critical programs established following
         SECNAV's Quality of Service memorandum. This directive, stemming from the recommendations of the USS George
         Washington (CVN-73) Phase II report directly confronts the challenge of Sailor suicide and underscores the Navy's
         commitment to the Sailor. This investment enables data-driven decision-making, ensuring that initiatives designed to improve
         QoS and increase retention are performing effectively and enhancing warfighter readiness. (Baseline: $123,354)
      iv)MyNavy HR IT Modernization and Sustainment: Modernization resources increased for transition of Authoritative Data                      8,662
         Environment (ADE) into Advana/Jupiter and for Enterprise Customer Relationship Management (eCRM) modernization.
         ADE resources increased to migrate to Advana/Jupiter the existing legacy data warehouses into and sustain a central data
         repository that is composed of a data warehouse, data lake, data management tools and an Application Program Interface
         (API) Layer. eCRM resources increased to integrate and sustain business processes, supporting systems, and authoritative
         data in support of Navy Personnel Command's (NPC's) MyNavy Career Center (MNCC), Navy Recruiting Command (NRC),
         Navy Education & Training Command (NETC), and other commands that manage the Navy's workforce. (Baseline:
         $109,214)
      v)MyNavy Career Center (MNCC):Increase in civilian personnel funding to meet SECWAR's top priorities. Funding supports                     7,188
         key headquarters program management activities and, most critically, provides the requisite workforce for the Navy's
         Personnel Support Detachments (PSDs). These positions are integral to the execution of all personnel and pay actions for the
         all-volunteer force. Ensuring the quality and timeliness of these transactions is a key objective of the Chief of Naval
         Personnel. This investment directly enables force readiness by ensuring the navy's administrative support systems function
         effectively, which is a prerequisite for sustaining a proficient and mission-focused naval service. (Baseline: $195,363; +87
         civilian FTE)
      vi)Personnel and Manpower Support Programs: Increased funding is required to establish evidence-based wellness programs                    4,558
         that provide proactive behavioral health support to at-risk Sailors. These initiatives address key findings from the USS
         George Washington report by providing Sailors with early access to licensed clinicians for non-medical counseling and
         resilience training. The model focuses on mitigating risk factors associated with harmful behaviors and suicide by addressing
         stressors before they escalate to a clinical diagnosis requiring long-term care. This represents a fiscally responsible strategy to
         preserve human capital, reduce lost duty days, and ensure the long-term operational effectiveness of personnel in demanding
         roles. (Baseline: $123,354; +2 civilian FTE)

