planning for and responding to emergencies (natural/man-made disasters, terrorist attacks, etc.) and other military contingency operations and NAVFAC's emergency management
responsibilities to plan and prepare for emergencies.

Real Estate Management
NAVFAC Real Estate Business Line is the Command's and Technical Authority for the acquisition, leasing, disposal, surveying, and appraisal of all Class 1 and Class 2 property
(RE) for DON Facility real estate acquisition and disposal includes real estate services and program management for such actions as purchases; sales; transfers; exchanges;
demolition; in-grants and out-grants; in-leases and out-leases; technical support to Public Private Venture (PPV) and Base Realignment and Closure (BRAC) disposals and
property conveyances, as required; and special legislation initiatives.

Ocean Facilities & Equipment Engineering
The Ocean Facilities & Equipment Engineering program manages and executes the planning, design, and maintenance of ocean facilities and equipment, including fixed ocean and
seafloor systems. Ocean Equipment are those specialized equipment and facilities components used primarily by the Underwater Teams and the Ocean Facilities Departments of
the Naval Facilities Engineering and Expeditionary Warfare Center to perform site selection, inspection, maintenance, repair, and removal of Fleet ocean facilities and
infrastructure.

CESE Maintenance and Operations
Naval Facilities serves as the single Navy manager of Civil Engineering Support Equipment (CESE), specifically with regard to Non-Tactical Vehicles (NTV) and Non-Tactical
Equipment (NTE).

Weight Handling Ashore
The Navy Crane Center (NCC) is responsible for all matters pertaining to the Department of the Navy weight-handling program including developing policy for training, program
management, acquisition, design criteria, maintenance, testing, certification, and operation of weight handling equipment. NCC is responsible to: evaluate WHE programs annually
or biennially in accordance with the SECNAVINST to ensure compliance with DON program requirements; provide validations for cranes in special applications and independent
third party certifications for cranes used in maritime applications; provide technical support to include approval of alterations to WHE including configuration control. NCC
analyzes Navy WHE accidents to improve safety.

Naval Sea Systems Command (NAVSEA)

Command Headquarters Administrative and Facilities Support:
Provides administrative support costs for the NAVSEA Contracts personnel who provide centralized procurement and contract administration services. Administrative support
costs include, travel, training, supplies, and purchased services. Provides for facility support services and facility maintenance in NAVSEA Headquarters occupied buildings in the
Washington Navy Yard. Provides Physical Security for NAVSEA HQ, Washington Navy Yard, and provides other services and facility maintenance that directly affect the
physical security of NAVSEA HQ.

Shipboard Environmental Protection:
Shipboard Environmental Protection funding are used to improve the Fleet's ability to comply with afloat environmental planning requirements, environmental discharge and usage
requirements, and cybersecurity compliance requirements in accordance with applicable federal statutes , DoW and Navy instructions in the areas of solid and plastic waste
management, hazardous material control and management (including paints and toxic substances), sewage and graywater, oily wastes, oil spills, engine exhausts, ballast water, and
Uniform National Discharge Standard (UNDS) discharges. Specifically, funding are used to provide direct Fleet support (e.g., groom support), lifecycle management (LCM), and
       631                                                                                                                                                 $$, $$fd4f900cbf5834c54464627f1b9c9b8b06db1cfd2e769872ea40fb7fde6e6bce$$, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, NULL, $$2026-05-07T23:02:15.70986+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_activity_years (activity_code, fiscal_year, service, appropriation, ba, sag_short_code, title, prior_year_actual, current_year_enacted, request_amount, fydp_yr1, fydp_yr2, fydp_yr3, fydp_yr4, narrative, content_hash, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$OM_NAVY_X_590$$, 2027, $$Navy$$, $$OM_NAVY$$, NULL, NULL, $$Department of the Navy$$, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, $$, 4B2N
                                                                                                                                                                  (Page 3 of 16)
                                                                                 Department of the Navy
                                                                         FY 2027 President's Budget Submission
                                                                            Operation and Maintenance, Navy
                                                                Budget Activity: Administration and Servicewide Activities
                                                               Activity Group: Logistics Operations And Technical Support
                                                        Detail by Subactivity Group: Planning, Engineering, and Program Support
in-service engineering (ISE) support for shipboard environmental systems and equipment. LCM and ISE support includes correction of deficiencies and obsolescence issues for
shipboard systems and equipment, and improvements to Fleet reliability, maintainability, availability (RMA), and affordability issues.
Funding also supports active statutory compliance-driven modernization programs such as the Oil Pollution Abatement (OPA) Improvements program, Large Pulper
Improvements program, Hazardous Material Minimization Center (HAZMINCEN) program, and Dry Waste Processing Suites (DWPS) Improvements program. Funding to
support these programs are used to develop the Integrated Logistics Support (ILS) of newly installed equipment per these programs, provide installation technical support, and
provide training to ship's force on operation and maintenance of new systems and equipment.
Additional environmental efforts supported include:
(i) Oversight of mission-critical reserve of Ozone Depleting Substances (ODSs) to ensure that the existing reserve meets future submarine requirements;
(ii) Diesel and gas turbine engine exhaust emissions calculations and monitoring;
(iii) Shipboard paint reformulation to reduce the frequency of painting operations, as well as reduce volatile organic compound (VOC) levels and hazardous air pollutant (HAP)
levels required to meet federal, state, and local air pollution requirements;
(iv) Establish cybersecurity compliance requirements for shipboard environmental equipment, obtain Authorization to Operate (ATO) certification, and maintain cybersecurity
requirements.

Radiation Detection:
Radiation Detection, Indication & Computation (RADIAC) instruments detect and measure ionizing radiation in order to protect personnel and the environment from the effects of
exposure to radiation. Navy's Nuclear Propulsion, Nuclear Weapons, Industrial Radiography, Medical, Radiological Defense, Explosive Ordnance Disposal, and Consequence
Management programs use RADIAC instruments. Provides centralized life cycle engineering, logistical, and information technology support, demilitarization of RADIACs, and
disposal of radioactive sources.

Radiation Control and Health Program:
Provides management and oversight of Naval Radiation Protection Programs including the Radiological Affairs Support Program (RASP), Low Level Radioactive Waste Program
(LLRW), and Historical Radiological Assessments (HRA). Programs protect workers, the public, and the environment from receiving undue radiation exposure from DON
activities. RASP provides regulatory inspections, emergency response, radioactive material license evaluations, DON radiation safety courses, development of program policy and
procedures, payment of Nuclear Regulatory Commission license fees, and collection and maintenance of DON personnel radiation exposure data. LLRW provides collection,
packaging, processing, and burial of radioactive waste generated by DON commands. HRA develops and issues assessments of Navy radiological impact on the environment.

Hull, Mechanical & Electrical Support:
Executes Technical Authority and Systems Engineering throughout the life cycle of ships and ship systems. Fills the gaps between program offices to engineer cross-program
solutions and common standards, focuses on a systems engineering approach, and ensures safety. Creates and maintains Technical Authority Policy documentation, Technical
Standards, and Qualified Products Lists.

Damage Control, Fire protection:
(1) Damage Control In-Service Engineering provides engineering and logistics support for maintaining Naval Ships Technical Manual. (2) Personnel protection in-service
engineering provides engineering and logistics support for Self-Contained Breathing Apparatus (SCBA) fire fighter's breathing apparatus, firefighter's protective clothing, flash
gear and life preservers. (3) Fire Protection. This effort provides in-service engineering for fire extinguishing systems and engineering expertise for fire hazard analysis and
material fire performance assessment. This effort supports and maintains the Naval Ship Technical Manual "Surface Ship Firefighting". The Damage Control, Personnel Protection
and Fire Protection. Programs supports all surface ships. Most Damage Control and Fire Protection equipment are used across all platforms. This effort also provides engineering
support for the Navy Shock Program to ensure the fleet utilizes appropriately qualified Shock items.
